---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import MerkabaEarthMapApplet from '../../components/MerkabaEarthMapApplet.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro'; // Assuming you have or want a header
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro'; // Assuming you have or want a footer
---

<Layout title="The Merkaba Earth Grid - An Interactive Exploration">
  <Header />
  <main class="container">
    <article>
      <header>
        <h1>The Merkaba, Sacred Geometry, and Earth's Energetic Grid</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">An interactive journey into ancient mysteries and planetary energies.</p>
      </header>
      <section>
        <h2>What is the Merkaba?</h2>
        <p>
          The Merkaba is a profound symbol in sacred geometry, often described as a
          star tetrahedron – a three-dimensional Star of David. It's considered by
          many spiritual traditions to be a divine light vehicle, an energy field
          that can be activated around the human body. This field is believed to
          facilitate spiritual ascension, interdimensional travel, and a deeper
          connection with higher states of consciousness.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2>The Earth Grid Theory</h2>
        <p>
          Fascinating theories propose that the Merkaba's geometric pattern isn't
          limited to personal energy fields but also maps onto the Earth itself,
          forming a vast, interconnected energetic grid. According to these ideas,
          key megalithic structures and sacred sites around the world – such as the
          Great Pyramid of Giza, Stonehenge, Machu Picchu, and many others – are
          not randomly placed. Instead, they are thought to be strategically
          located at the vertices, nodes, or significant intersection points of
          this planetary grid.
        </p>
        <p>
          These sites may act as energetic hotspots, conduits, or amplifiers,
          channeling and distributing cosmic and terrestrial energies across the
          globe. The precise geometry of this grid is a subject of ongoing research
          and speculation, often involving complex polyhedral shapes like the
          icosahedron or dodecahedron, in addition to the star tetrahedron.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2>Explore the Merkaba Earth Map</h2>
        <p>
          Below is an interactive applet designed to help you visualize one
          interpretation of the Merkaba Earth Map. Engage with the model to see
          how these ancient structures might align and interconnect through this
          geometric energy matrix.
        </p>

        <MerkabaEarthMapApplet />

        <p>
          This exploration encourages us to ponder the advanced knowledge potentially
          possessed by ancient civilizations. Did they understand Earth's subtle
          energies and cosmic principles in ways we are only beginning to rediscover?
          What other secrets might this global energetic network hold?
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h2>Further Thoughts</h2>
        <p>
          While the concept of a Merkaba-based Earth grid is compelling, it's
          important to approach it with a blend of open-mindedness and critical
          thinking. The study of ley lines, sacred geometry, and archaeoastronomy
          continues to evolve, offering new perspectives on our planet's hidden
          dimensions and our ancestors' wisdom.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .container {
    max-width: 900px; /* Slightly wider for blog content */
    margin: 2rem auto; /* Add some top/bottom margin */
    padding: 0 1rem; /* Keep horizontal padding */
  }
  article {
    background-color: var(--color-bg-alt, #1a1a1a); /* Use a subtle background for the article */
    padding: 2rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
  }
  header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border, #444);
    padding-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  h1 {
    font-size: 2.8rem; /* Adjust as per your global styles or preference */
    color: var(--accent, #883aea); /* Use accent color */
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: var(--accent-light, #e0cafa);
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: var(--accent-light, #e0cafa);
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border, #444);
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  p {
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
    line-height: 1.7; /* Slightly more line height for readability */
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
  section {
    margin-bottom: 2rem; /* Add space between sections */
    padding: 0; /* Override default section padding from global styles if any */
  }
  /* Ensure the applet container itself doesn't get unwanted global section padding */
  section > MerkabaEarthMapApplet {
    padding: 0;
  }
</style>
